abstract: N.W. Pike, of No. 599 Sixth avenue, NewYork, formerly of Plainfield, N. J., was arrested yesterday afternoon at Elizabeth by Under Sheriff Nichol. He was allowed to attend the funeral this afternoon under escort, and will probably give bail.

abstract: CINCINNATI, July, 9. A dispatch to J.H. Rhodes, Superintendent of Adams Express Company, states that a desperate attempt to rob Express Messenger Burke was made at Long Point, Ill., on the Vanadalia Railroad, last night. abstract: CAPE MAY, July 13. If everything militated against the regatta yesterday, everything favored it to-day. Yesterday it was sombre, dull, stagnant. To-day it was clear sunshine, with sparkling waves and a breeze that was a perfect balm to the heart of a yachtsman. In the morning the wind was southwest, very light, as it nearly always is in the early hours of the day, but it gave good promise.

abstract: The late trains last night and the early ones this morning brought up immense crowds, and Saratoga began to put on a gala appearance. The attendance, however, was not nearly so great as last year. The morning broke with a cloudless sky and with just the faintest whisper of a breeze. Disheveled heads peering out of chamber windows pronounced the prospect "lovely," and contentment reigned over the matutinal toilet.

abstract: WASHINGTON, July 17.--The reports of the existence of yellow at Norfolk have been investigated to-day, and to all inquiries answers come that there are no cases. The subject was brought up at the Board of Health meeting here last night, and it was determined that Washington should be quarantined against Norfolk if the reports that were afloat should be found correct.

Morrison and his assistants left Fort Garland about twelve days ago, moving in a south-westerly direction, and finally reaching this queer little Mexican town of Tierra Amarilla, after passing through some of the most picturesque sections of Colorado.
